                     <hi rend="largeCaps">THOMAS BROOKER</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430130-834-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430130-834-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430130-834-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>for unlawfully uttering coun<lb></lb>terfeit coin, knowing the same to be counterfeit.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. CHAMBERS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">CHARNOCK</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">ELIZAWILLIAMS</hi>. I am the wife of Samuel Williams, a cow-keeper, in the Old Kent-road. On the 13th of Jan. the prisoner came for a penny-worth of milk—I served him a halfpenny-worth by mistake—he gave me a shilling—I told him it was bad—he said he did not know it, he would go and get me 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for the milk, if I would take the mug of milk and give him the shilling—I said I would not return the shilling, but detain him—I sent for an officer—the prisoner walked out of the yard till he got round the corner, then he ran—he left the shilling in my hand—I called a policeman, gave him the shilling, and he gave it me back again—I put it on a shelf, and the next morning I marked it and gave it to the officer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1434" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1434" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1434" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1434" type="given" value="ANNE MARIA"></interp>ANNE MARIA BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with a cow-keeper, in Great George-street, Bermondsey. About nine o'clock in the evening of the 13th of Jan. the pri<lb></lb>soner came for a halfpenny-worth of milk—I served him—he gave me a shil<lb></lb>ling—I took it to my master—I am sure I gave him the same shilling.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1435" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1435" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1435" type="surname" value="DUCKETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1435" type="given" value="MARK"></interp>MARK DUCKETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am Brown's master—she gave me a shilling on the 13th of Jan.—I marked it and gave it to the policeman—I came out and saw the prisoner in my shop, and said, "We have been taking some bad money; I am doubtful whether you might not have been passing some here"—he said he had not—I sent my man fora policeman, and gave him in charge—I went</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184301300271"></xptr>
               <p>into a shop in the neighbourhood to weigh the shilling—it proved a bad one—the prisoner said he lived in a street just by the lamp-post.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1436" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1436" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1436" type="surname" value="RAWLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1436" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS RAWLEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 269.) I took the prisoner on the 13th—I produce the shilling given me by Duckett.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1437" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1437" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1437" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1437" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>MR. JOHN FIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. These are both counterfeit, and both cast in one mould—this last one is very easily detected.</p>
